odern sense, but that it was so novel that outsiders did not know what to make of it. He describes how, as the old order unraveled, the communes emerged, governed by consular elites "chosen by the people," and subject to neither emperor nor king. They regularly fought each other, yet they grew organized and confident enough to ally together to defeat Frederick Barbarossa, the German emperor, at the Battle of Legnano in 1176.Sleepwalking into a New World reveals how the development of the autonomous city-state took place, which would in the end make possible the robust civic culture of the Renaissance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCity-stateszItalyxHistory. 0aCommunal livingzItalyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEmilia.  aItaly.  aLombardy.  aMilan.  aPiemonte.  aPisa.  aRenaissance.  aRomagna.  aRome.  aTuscany.  aVeneto.  aaristocracy.  aaristocrats.  aassemblies.  aautonomous city-states.  acivic culture.  acivic pride.  acollaboration.  acollective government.  acolloquium.  acommerce.  acommunes.  aconsuls.  aelite.  afamilies.  ahistoriography.  ainstitutional creativity.  amilitary.  apapacy.  apapal reform.  apolitical history.  aélite.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140086582640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400865826423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400865826.jpg  a978-3-11-066592-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK